[1]
Date: Sat, 22 Jan 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Nation, Bangkok, 22 Jan 2005 [edited]
<http://www.nationmultimedia.com/2005/01/22/national/index.php?news=national_16160183.html>

Bird flu: Officials told to keep an eye out
-------------------------------------------
Provincial officials have been requested to be on watch for bird-flu
outbreaks, Yukol Limlaemthong, director-general of the Livestock
Development Department, said yesterday [21 Jan 2004].
"Bird-flu watch centres will be headed by provincial governors while
district chiefs monitor activities at the local level. Daily reports will
be sent to the department to ensure suspect cases are investigated without
delay," Yukol said.
He urged farmers to cull birds that show avian flu symptoms and said
poultry-transporters must have proof of random virus-tests before chickens
are taken to slaughter.
Yukol said that in the past 2 months the department had arranged for
antiseptic spraying of farms around the country, especially where ducks
were reared, as it was known these could look healthy but still carry the
disease.
He added that Phitsanulok and Rayong were under the 21-day bird-flu watch
but other provinces had not reported any ill or dead poultry.
He also warned chicken-raisers to apply early next month for permission to
transport chickens before selling them for Chinese New Year celebrations.
If they try to move them without the necessary documents, farmers will be
subject to a 2-year jail term for breaking the Animal Quarantine Act, he said.
Meanwhile Rayong livestock development officer Santi Atchayutpokin, said
laboratory tests on chickens in Rayong's Klaeng district had found no
traces of the virus.
The tests were conducted on chickens in a 5-kilometre radius of a farm
where 20 chickens with bird flu were culled on 12 Jan 2005, he
said. Additional tests were carried out in the same area late yesterday,
and the results should be known in 7 days, he said. Meanwhile no poultry
may be transported out of the area.
Rayong public-health official Dr Wiwat Wiriyakijja said his colleagues
running health checks on people living in the control area had not reported
any cases of people with symptoms similar to those of bird flu. However,
all hospitals have been instructed to isolate patients with respiratory
problems as a precaution.
In related news, on Tuesday [25 Jan 2005] Chiang Mai livestock-development
officer Somporn Pornwisetkul is to meet public-health officials and
concerned agencies to discuss measures to deal with any outbreak of bird
flu to prevent it from spreading to the upper northern provinces.
Salakjit Chutivivet, head of the Chiang Mai medical-science centre's human
bird-flu laboratory, said that since the laboratory opened last year,
government and private hospitals had been sending 10-20 tissue samples a
month to be tested for the H5N1 virus, but to date no cases had been found.
Salakjit said 6 samples had come from hospitals in Chiang Mai Muang and San
Pa Tong districts.
--
