[2]
Date: 22 Jan 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Voice of Vietnam [edited]
<http://www.vov.org.vn/2005_01_22/english/xahoi1.htm#PM%20orders%20strong%20actions%20to%20stop%20spread%20of%20bird%20flu>

PM orders strong actions to stop spread of bird flu
-----------------
*** The Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development reported on Saturday
that bird flu has spread to 232 communes in 23 cities and provinces
nationwide, with more than 500 000 chickens, ducks and quails being culled.
After Hanoi and Ha Nam, Hai Duong is the 3rd locality in the northern
region to be affected by bird flu, with the latest outbreaks detected on
Saturday morning. The Mekong Delta still has the highest outbreaks so far.
The Ministry sent a report on developments of the disease to the Government
and asked for VND80 billion to purchase medical equipment, respirators and
chemicals for the 3 regions across the country.
*** Earlier, on Thursday, Deputy Prime Minister Pham Gia Khiem, on behalf
of the Prime Minister, ordered ministries, ministerial-level agencies,
government agencies and provincial and municipal People's Committees to
take strict measures to prevent the spread of pneumonia caused by the
type-A flu virus (H5N1).
*** The prevention of avian influenza and its transmission to humans must
be given top, Deputy Prime Minister Nguyen Tan Dzung told an
inter-provincial meeting in Hanoi on Friday.
He asked localities and the mass media to boost information dissemination
to raise public awareness about avian influenza. He requested both
unaffected and affected areas to tighten control over poultry slaughtering,
processing and transportation to prevent the epidemic from spreading.
He also asked big cities and towns nationwide to mark out areas for poultry
trading, slaughtering and processing, and ordered a temporary suspension of
poultry imports from neighbouring countries.
*** HCM City's Veterinary Department is co-ordinating closely with the
municipal Market Watch Force and Police 113 to work round the clock along
national highways and inter-provincial roads to stop the transport of
poultry and poultry products into the city. The city has established 56
safe slaughterhouses under the strict scrutiny of veterinarians.
*** MARD Minister Cao Duc Phat is requesting Hanoi to mark off poultry
slaughter houses and prevent the transport of poultry of unknown origin
into the city. The city has established 13 checkpoints at city gates and
another 30 at markets.
*** In central Quang Nam province, bird flu has spread to 7 communes and
wards. 60 out of 124 test samples showed positive for H5N1. Chairman of the
provincial People's Committee Nguyen Xuan Phuc ordered local authorities to
cull sick and infected poultry and fine households which have not
co-operated with bird flu prevention forces. Da Nang city alone has
established a hot telephone line to deal with issues relating to the flu.
